---
import Docs from '../../layouts/Docs.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../components/CodeBlock.astro';

const headings = [
  { depth: 2, slug: 'why-migrations', text: 'Why migrations' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'declaring-a-version', text: 'Declaring a version' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'writing-a-step', text: 'Writing a migration step' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'renaming-and-backfilling', text: 'Renaming and backfilling' },
  { depth: 2, slug: 'rules-of-thumb', text: 'Rules of thumb' },
];

const version = `export const db = createLedger(
  { users: collection<User>({ key: 'id' }) },
  {
    persist: indexedDB({ name: 'app' }),
    schemaVersion: 3,
    migrations: {
      2: addFullName,
      3: splitName,
    },
  }
);`;

const step = `// A migration receives a tx scoped to the upgrade and runs exactly once,
// in order, before the store becomes ready.
function addFullName(tx) {
  for (const user of tx.users.all()) {
    tx.users.update(user.id, {
      fullName: \`\${user.first} \${user.last}\`,
    });
  }
}`;

const rename = `// v3: split a single 'fullName' back into first / last and drop the old field.
function splitName(tx) {
  for (const user of tx.users.all()) {
    const [first, ...rest] = (user.fullName ?? '').split(' ');
    tx.users.update(user.id, {
      first,
      last: rest.join(' '),
    });
    tx.users.unset(user.id, 'fullName');
  }
}`;
---

<Docs
  title="Schema migrations"
  description="Evolve your stored data shape safely with versioned schemas and ordered migration steps."
  headings={headings}
>
  <span class="eyebrow">Guides</span>
  <h1>Schema migrations</h1>
  <p class="lead">
    Apps change shape. When your record types evolve, persisted data on a user's device
    still has the old shape — migrations bring it up to date, in order and exactly once,
    before your code ever reads it.
  </p>

  <h2 id="why-migrations">Why migrations</h2>
  <p>
    A persisted store may contain data written by any past version of your app. Without
    migrations you'd have to defensively handle every historical shape forever. Instead,
    you describe the steps from one version to the next and Ledger replays whichever ones
    a given device still needs.
  </p>

  <h2 id="declaring-a-version">Declaring a version</h2>
  <p>
    Bump <code>schemaVersion</code> whenever your record shape changes, and register a
    migration for each new version number:
  </p>
  <CodeBlock code={version} lang="ts" file="db.ts" />
  <p>
    A device on version 1 runs <code>2</code> then <code>3</code>. A device on version 2 runs only
    <code>3</code>. A fresh install jumps straight to the current version and runs nothing.
  </p>

  <h2 id="writing-a-step">Writing a migration step</h2>
  <p>
    Each step gets an upgrade transaction with the same query and mutation API you already know.
    It runs once, then Ledger records the new version on disk.
  </p>
  <CodeBlock code={step} lang="ts" />

  <h2 id="renaming-and-backfilling">Renaming and backfilling</h2>
  <p>Migrations are just code, so renames, splits, and backfills are straightforward:</p>
  <CodeBlock code={rename} lang="ts" />
  <div class="callout callout--warn">
    <span class="callout__icon" aria-hidden="true">⚠️</span>
    <p>Migrations are not reversible. If a user downgrades the app, an older build won't understand a newer <code>schemaVersion</code> and will refuse to load that store. Treat version bumps as forward-only.</p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="rules-of-thumb">Rules of thumb</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>One version per shipped change.</strong> Never edit a migration that's already in production — add the next one.</li>
    <li><strong>Keep steps pure and deterministic.</strong> No network calls; a migration must finish from local data alone.</li>
    <li><strong>Backfill, don't assume.</strong> New required fields need a default for every existing record.</li>
    <li><strong>Test the chain.</strong> Seed a v1 store in a test and assert it ends up correct at the latest version.</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="callout callout--tip">
    <span class="callout__icon" aria-hidden="true">💡</span>
    <p>In development you can pass <code>onMigrate: 'log'</code> to print each step and its record counts as it runs — useful for catching a backfill that missed rows.</p>
  </div>
</Docs>
